A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in the 'hot' HIV virus
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can moderate the spread of HIV in the organism
The main advantage of this improved substance is that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, such as some already accessible medicines.
AIDS can't be cured so far.
However, patients' lives may be significantly extended by a mixture of medicines that prevent the replication of HIV in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If virus replication is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, medicines no longer work.
The work of experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and Heidelberg University demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalocarborans have an effect on albumin, responsible for the spread of HIV.
Metalocarbons are composed of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way other than all medicines used today, and that is why they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists find new, ‘best’ compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the albumin of the virus.
The metalocarborans have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedron cages composed by the atoms of boron, hydrogen and carbon are joined by the atom of metal, in this case by cobalt.
A Traitor and Resistant Virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and it is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV protease, the fractionation of the HIV virus does not occur and no mature and infectious body of the virus would be created.
If we stop the HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, explain scientists in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In an article published in the journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds, in which two pairs of cages (see table) are joined by a short organic series, which continues to be systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more effective
Test of the effect of this series of HIV protease substances was carried out in probes, and also against their resistant variants obtained from HIV patients.
The effect of metalocarborans on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as in clinically used drugs, however they do not lose their effect on resistant variants, in which drugs often do not work.
The mechanism of the single effect, its other qualities such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications, makes metalocarborans interesting compounds for research with the aim of proposing effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina ¢ezáčová, the head of the structural biology laboratory at the Institute of Organic and Biochemical Chemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics in the Academy of Sciences.
