A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, so far characterized by challenging positions and mutual recriminations, caught renewed attention on Friday with the dissemination of a document that foresees ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiations that are running out of time, with over 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Developed by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not talk about how much money the rich countries would give to the poor to face global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit to the overall increase in the temperature that political strategies would be willing to tolerate.
This gives the process a lot of flexibility, said John Coequyt, high representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's maximum climate officer, Yvo de Boer, described as - the big picture -
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations collectively cut their emissions by 2020 by between 25 and 45 per cent, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their emissions during the same period by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, the countries would cut emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also encouraged talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years, to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, Friday was the same kind of verbal fireworks that dominated the talks last week.
The United States Special Climate Envoy, Todd Stern, rejected claims that require mandatory greenhouse gas emissions reductions for industrialized countries, compared with volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is adopting a tougher line with China, with respect to what Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States is not going to make an agreement without the major developing countries moving forward and taking action, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern commented an hour after the Chinese Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs He Yafei stated that the greatest climate negotiator in the United States lacked, or was, very irresponsible because he had said earlier in the week that the United States would not help China economically to cope with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, the fault lines have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The present battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries in the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a Costa Rican delegate, said it is not surprising that the main powers are discussing who should cost the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even though the vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in their efforts to contain the major issuers responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is being developed, said Ulate, who also works as a regional adviser on climate change in Mexico and Central America for International Conservation.
Some of the most vulnerable countries to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants said that the talks would produce a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, developed a proposal for a 24-page preliminary treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the push of small island nations has, in part, put political pressure on the whole political process, because they are now unified and require the action of emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the outstanding issues before the heads of government came to a close.
High-level officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister, came down from the planes and ran to the Bella Center corridors, closed-door meetings and press conferences, so that they could delineate the claims that will be made during the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where every day 13,000 people enter and leave the convention center, the activists who play the guitar present night shows mocking the countries that they think are selling, and hand-to-hand proposals are passed instead of via mail), poses a challenge.
The intensity only builds: almost all key ministers are here right now, and on Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, vice-president for the global policy of International Conservation.
Heavy weights are coming.
