Management Revolution or End of Business Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of the big French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with respect to their employees recalls the position of companies with respect to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about the employees joining - values - determined from above as before it was about imposing on consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer in the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to the strategies to conquer the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to the preference factors of the customers is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can end up in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R & D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, the BI (Business Intelligence) - requires that all parties involved (...) have proactive conduct and a prospective vision - it needs a commitment from employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian direction.
For this reason, we call for a managerial revolution, which would consist of putting the collaborators at the center of the company's concerns as well as the client.
Internal opinion surveys have a relative usefulness
Do internal opinion surveys, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among his employees, encourage the managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I could verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many turns, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
- Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
-Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from large engineering schools, they interpret psychology in a mechanical way.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behavioral theory that the Americans recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely spread behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the \"commands\" (sic) of the commitment of executives, a recent research by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the managers in a mechanistic management position, inadequate to the world today.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the good functioning of modern companies, involves adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into all reasoning or business management practice, a fundamental fact: for the employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make its dreams, ambitions and projects a reality.
Today, only studies from the Motivational Analysis adopt this conception of the motivations of employees.
The studies showed that they judge their company based on a default dox that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
With the identification and measurement of mobilisation factors, business managers can control, predict and anticipate their \"social performance\" and relocate human resource management in place.
In this way, they create a favourable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
