The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa found the same look as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-metre-long and 1.50-foot-high animal running on the two strong hind legs, had a long head with sharp teeth and curves, short arms with claws shaped like hoz and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple million years later, it would not have been something special.
But Tawa foundlae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the Thursday Science magazine.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry area of the Pangea supercontinent on the equator.
Tawa opened a new window towards the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt comments.
It shows us much about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes, we have found in one day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is something unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis member of the Utah Museum of Natural History team.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation the remains of five specimens gathered in total.
A find confirms the theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name - Tawa - comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt is an exceptional finding: -The dinosaur fossils of the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found -
Other dinosaur experts do not fully share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, comments for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current trend of opinion, dinosaurs appeared for the first time about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, the experts discuss, for example, when the sauaries were divided into their three most important genealog lines: the carnivorous terropods among which the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauropods known as the long neck, and their relatives, and the herbivorous Ornithischia (sauri with ave pelvis), to whom, for example, the Triceratops and Stegosaurus species belong.
According to Nesbitt's analysis and his colleagues, Tawa foundlae is a primitive teropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, comments Nesbitt.
For example, in the Tawa skull, researchers found signs of air bags, such as those that also possess the descents of the teropods, birds.
Thanks to air bags, birds' breathing is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa find also the bones of the spine were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the teropod with oldest and most primitive air bags, Randall Irmis comments.
Because the parent line of the subsequent giant sauropods also had air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups would already produce this useful innovation.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known lived in South America, researchers conclude that the sauaries first emerged there.
Therefore, the three genealogical lines separated at an early stage and spread from South America through all the corners of the Earth, which by then still formed a unique earth mass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say that the team found together with Tawa find the remains of two other teropods not closely related.
The three cannot descend from a single parented predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three migratory waves were made to North America, comments Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science Study.
Of course, there are opponents as well.
An even older species, Silesaurus, who belongs to a brother group of dinosaurs, lived in the present-day Poland, comments by the paleontologist of Bonn Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still being preserved, while in other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs were able to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of Mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic dinosaurs still shared their vital space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of the present crocodiles and the pterosaurus and many other sauries.
Towards the end of the Triassic dinosaurs expanded throughout the world and many new species developed, while the kinship became extinct at the limit of the Triassic towards Jurassic.
Success stories were not eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, Martin Sander comments.
There could have been a massive extinction to which dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or dinosaurs were better suited, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Success stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, an impact of meteorite brakes the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then carried a miserable existence: mammals.
