The study points out that there are many differences in the start of cohabitation in couples and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an out-of-home activity, work part-time, or have a non-steady job, begin first cohabitation in marriage, advance first motherhood, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay coexistence and maternity, and have less offspring.
The women between 35 and 49 years of age with fixed work have the first child, on average, 3.7 years after the start of life, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs has taken longer of their vital path to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a great deal of influence on motherhood, although less on the mating schedule, explains the researcher of CSIC Margarita Delgado.
The level of study is another factor that differentiates the age of women when they marry and have the first stroke.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the older the age they marry and the one the first child has.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those with elementary and higher studies have been mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
In addition, another division is established among women according to their level of study.
