Emergency braking aid is already mandatory
As was the case with the ABS brake antilock and will pass with the ESP stability control, emergency braking aid systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, this is already the case for all new registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest, a period of deficiency is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase pedestrian protection although, by its way of work, it can also help to avoid many collisions in scope.
The emergency braking assistant does what he does is to increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the driver's treadmill.
But this one doesn't always keep that pressure to the end.
According to a study carried out by the manufacturer of components for Bosch car, the third part of the drivers involved in an accident had not been able to step the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum braking system, reducing the distance the car uses to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with such elements, they could be avoided by the year up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one out of every four sinisters would be avoided with damage to people - when the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems are popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects the obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps to increase pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
